  "prompt": "How much to charge for glowsticks at a party 50 person Halloween party? I don\u2019t want to seem miserly at a party where everything else is free",
  "response": "Pricing glowsticks at a 50-person Halloween party can be tricky since you want to balance covering your costs with not seeming miserly. Here\u2019s a thoughtful approach:\n\n### 1. **Cost Recovery + Symbolic Fee**\nSince everything else at the party is free, you could charge a **nominal fee** to cover your costs without making guests feel like they\u2019re paying too much. For example:\n- If glowsticks cost you **$0.50 each**, you could charge **$1 per glowstick**.\n- This allows you to recover your costs while keeping it affordable and fun.\n\n### 2. **Bundle Pricing**\nOffer a small bundle for a slightly better deal:\n- **$5 for 6 glowsticks**. This encourages people to buy more while keeping the price reasonable.\n\n### 3. **Set a Ceiling**\nConsider setting a **maximum charge per person**. For example, if someone wants 10 glowsticks, cap their total at $5 or $6.\n\n### 4. **Free Initial Glowsticks**\nTo avoid seeming miserly, you could **give out one free glowstick per guest** and charge for extras. This creates goodwill while still covering costs for those who want more.\n\n### Example Pricing:\n- **First glowstick: Free**\n- **Additional glowsticks: $1 each or $5 for 6**\n\n### Estimated Revenue:\nIf everyone buys 2 glowsticks (one free, one paid):\n- **50 people x $1 = $50**\n\nIf some buy more bundles:\n- Potential revenue could be **$50\u2013$100**, depending on demand.\n\nThis approach ensures you\u2019re not out of pocket while keeping the vibe festive and generous!",
